@prefix : <#> .
@prefix schema: <http://schema.org/> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

: a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:about :sparqlAbsolutePrefixIRI ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-15T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-06-15T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

:sparqlAbsolutePrefixIRI a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "SPARQL Accordion PREFIX IRIs Must Be Absolute DAV IRIs"@en ;
    schema:description "All PREFIX declarations in SPARQL queries embedded in HTML infographic accordion blocks must use absolute IRIs derived from the DAV path pattern in the skills contract. Relative IRIs fail at remote SPARQL endpoints because there is no local base to resolve against."@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-15T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-06-15T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:step :step1, :step2, :step3, :step4, :step5 .

:step1 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 1 ;
    schema:name "Understand why relative IRIs fail at remote endpoints"@en ;
    schema:text """A SPARQL query embedded in an HTML accordion is URL-encoded and sent as a query parameter to a remote SPARQL endpoint (e.g., https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/sparql).

The endpoint receives only the query text as a string — it has no knowledge of the filesystem from which the HTML was generated.

If a PREFIX declaration uses a relative IRI such as:
  PREFIX okf: <okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl#okf->

The endpoint attempts to resolve this relative to the base of the request URL (e.g., https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/), producing:
  https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl#okf-

This IRI does not exist at that location. The endpoint returns 0 results or a parse error, silently breaking the Run Query button."""@en .

:step2 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 2 ;
    schema:name "Derive the absolute DAV IRI from the skills contract"@en ;
    schema:text """Read the DAV path pattern from the active skill. The canonical pattern from rdf-infographic-skill/SKILL.md and kg-generator/SKILL.md is:

  https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/{filename}.ttl

Procedure:
  1. Identify the ontology or vocabulary TTL filename (e.g., okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl).
  2. Substitute into the DAV pattern:
       https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl
  3. Append the fragment separator and class/property prefix fragment:
       https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl#okf-
  4. Use this as the absolute PREFIX IRI:
       PREFIX okf: <https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl#okf->

NEVER ask the user for this path. It is always derivable from the skills contract."""@en .

:step3 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 3 ;
    schema:name "Apply the absolute PREFIX IRI to both display and run-button targets"@en ;
    schema:text """There are two places where the PREFIX IRI appears in each SPARQL accordion:

(A) The sparql-code display block — the human-readable syntax-highlighted code.
    Replace the relative IRI in the <span class="iri"> element:
    Before: <span class="iri">&lt;okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl#okf-&gt;</span>
    After:  <span class="iri">&lt;https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/okf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl#okf-&gt;</span>

(B) The sparql-run-btn href — the URL-encoded query string.
    The IRI must be percent-encoded within the query parameter.
    Relative IRI (wrong):  %3Cokf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl%23okf-%3E
    Absolute IRI (correct): %3Chttps%3A%2F%2Flinkeddata.uriburner.com%2FDAV%2Fdemos%2Fdaas%2Fokf-open-knowledge-format-ontology.ttl%23okf-%3E

Both must be updated for each query. A display fix without fixing the href (or vice versa) leaves the accordion partially broken."""@en .

:step4 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 4 ;
    schema:name "Add the FROM clause to scope the query to the named graph"@en ;
    schema:text """After fixing the PREFIX IRI, also verify that each query includes a FROM clause scoping it to the instance-data named graph (per Step 41 / :step-virtuosoWorkbenchQueryDedup):

  FROM <https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/{instance-data-filename}.ttl>

This is separate from the PREFIX ontology IRI but equally required. Virtuoso is a quad store — without FROM, the query hits the union of all graphs and returns duplicates or misses.

The FROM graph IRI is the instance data TTL (not the ontology TTL), e.g.:
  FROM <https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/okf-open-knowledge-format-instance-data.ttl>

Add this clause between the SELECT ... variables line and the WHERE { block in both the display code and the URL-encoded href."""@en .

:step5 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 5 ;
    schema:name "Post-fix verification"@en ;
    schema:text """After editing all accordions, verify with grep:

Check no relative PREFIX IRIs remain in sparql-code blocks:
  grep -n 'class="iri"' file.html | grep -v 'https://' | grep -v 'http://'
  (Any match without http(s):// is a remaining relative IRI — fix it.)

Check all sparql-run-btn hrefs use percent-encoded absolute IRIs:
  grep -o 'href="https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/sparql[^"]*"' file.html | grep 'PREFIX'
  Confirm each contains the absolute DAV path (encoded as %2FDAV%2Fdemos%2Fdaas%2F or similar).

Check all queries have a FROM clause:
  grep -c 'FROM+%3Chttps%3A%2F%2Flinkeddata.uriburner.com%2FDAV' file.html
  Count should equal the number of SPARQL accordions."""@en .
